crops.origin: From Repetchek, near Amu Daria, Turkestan.
crops.description: "Ak-candym." (native Sart name, "ak" meaning white.) Planted along the Transcaspian Railway to bind the moving sands. All these bushes make excellent fuel.
Desert plant, not valuable for binding moving sands, but good on clay.

A native desert bush with linear leaves 3 inches long; attains a height of 15 feet; much planted to hold the moving sands along the Transcaspian Railway, and esteemed the best because the growth is quickest. Mr. Palettsky, the Government forestry expert in charge of this work, showed me one-year plants in nursery 5 feet high and well branched. This bush does well on sand and alkali deserts; the more it is cov-ered with moving sand the better it grows, as the branches root quickly. Wood heavier than water, good for fuel, but too brittle and hard to use in the arts.

crops.origin: From Repetchek, near Amu Daria, Turkestan.
crops.description: A variety. Desert plant, used in the same way as No. 196.

Used to bind the moving sand dunes along the Transcaspian Railway. A native, large, bushy, fleshy, leafless tree, which grows slowly at first but attains a height of 8 to 10 meters (24 to 30 feet ). Grows well in the sand deserts and on alkali soils. Wood makes excellent fuel, better than birch, heavier than water, but too brittle and hard to use in the arts.

crops.description: Desert plant. Used to bind the moving sands along the Transcaspian Railway.

Fruit somewhat pyriform, 1 by 1 inch in diameter, yellow, with red cheek. Tree much like mountain ash. Fruit much eaten when softened by partial decay, but to my taste this tree is of value only for ornament. Professor Hansen.
From Tiflis, Transcaucasia. Received through Prof. N. E. Hansen, March, 1898.
